Lab 6: Beyond chmod - Access Control Lists (ACLs)

Title: The Multi-Team Sharing Dilemma
Difficulty Level: Advanced
Objective: Use ACLs to grant specific permissions to multiple users on a single file without changing the file's primary owner or group. Standard chmod cannot do this.
Prerequisites: Install the ACL package (sudo apt install acl).


Environment Setup Commands:

mkdir -p ~/labs/security && cd ~/labs/security
touch deployment_secrets.txt
echo "DB_PASS=SuperSecret123" > deployment_secrets.txt
sudo useradd dev_alice
sudo useradd qa_bob


Tasks to Perform:

Check the current ACLs of the file using getfacl deployment_secrets.txt.

Give dev_alice explicit read and write access to the file using setfacl.

Give qa_bob explicit read-only access to the file.

Verify the new granular permissions. You will notice a + symbol at the end of the standard ls -l output, indicating ACLs are active.

Remove dev_alice's access entirely while keeping qa_bob's access intact.


1. getfacl deployment_secrets.txt
2. sudo setfacl -m u:dev_alice:rw deployment_secrets.txt
3. setfacl -m u:qa_bob:r deployment_secrets.txt